SWOMSE User Manual

Adrian Hordyk

August 2019

1 Introduction

The SWOMSE R package has been developed to conduct a management strategy evaluation (MSE) for the Atlantic swordfish fishery.

The package includes a collection of swordfish operating models (OMs), a swordfish data object, and management procedures (MPs) that can be evaluated with closed-loop simulation testing, and applied to the data object for management advice.

This document describes the contents SWOMSE R package, and illustrates how the package can be used to conduct the MSE and examine the results.

1.1 Installing the Package

The devtools package is required to install the SWOMSE package. Install the devtools package with:

install.packages('devtools')

The SWOMSE package can be either be installed directly from a GitHub repository (note that the repository is private so the authentication token must be used):

devtools::install_github("adrianhordyk/SWOMSE", 
                         auth_token = '36fe0145387ad05232ea376de6acecac43f0337a')

or from a local source file (e.g., ‘SWOMSE_0.1.0.tar.gz’):

install.packages('path_to_source', repos=NULL, type="source")

Once installed, the package can be loaded into the current R session:

library(SWOMSE)

2 The SWOMSE R Package

The SWOMSE package depends on the DLMtool and MSEtool R packages. Extensive help documentation is available for both packages by typing the following commands in the R console:

DLMtool::userguide()
MSEtool::userguide()

However, the SWOMSE package is designed to be self-contained and it is not be necessary to be familiar with the DLMtool or MSEtool R packages to run the MSE using the SWOMSE package.

This user guide is included as a vignette in the SWOMSE package and can be accessed with:

SWO_userguide()

The SWOMSE package follows the same object-oriented programming framework as DLMtool and MSEtool. This means that all objects and functions in the package are defined as specific classes that determines how the objects and treated.

There are three primary object classes that are used to run the MSE: OM, Data, and MP. These are described in the following sections.

2.1 Operating Models

Operating models are class OM and contain all parameters relating to the stock and fleet dynamics, as well as the observation and implementation processes.

There are 175 objects of class OM included in the SWOMSE package. The available OMs can be displayed using the avail command (here we just display the first 10):

OMs <- avail("OM")
OMs[1:10]
#>  [1] "SWOM"         "OM_base_case" "OM_19"        "OM_20"       
#>  [5] "OM_21"        "OM_22"        "OM_23"        "OM_24"       
#>  [9] "OM_25"        "OM_26"

The OMs included in the SWOMSE package have been constructed from the SS3 base case assessment and the converged SS3 assessments from the grid of uncertainties.

The first OM SWOM includes all of the SS3 assessments: the base case and the 173 converged OMs from the uncertainty grid. Each of the SS3 assessments is included as a separate simulation in the SWOM object.

The other 174 OMs in the SWOMSE package are the individual SS3 assessment OMs, including the base case assessment (OM_base_case) and the converged assessments from the uncertainty grid (e.g., OM_19 for assessment 19 - the first SS3 converged assessment, OM_20 for assessment 20, etc.)

The SWOM contains 174 simulations, corresponding to the base case OM, and the 173 OMs from the uncertainty grid.

The combined OM SWOM is used throughout this vignette. However, the analysis described here can be reproduced for any of the operating models be replacing SWOM with the name of the individual OM, for example, OM_base_case or OM_19.

2.1.1 Examining the OM Object

The contents of the operating model can be examined graphically using the plot function:

plot(SWOM)

This function generates a HTML file with histograms of all parameters in the operating model, as well as time-series plots of the historical population dynamics that are simulated by the model.

For convenience, the OM plot file is included in the package and can be viewed with:

browseURL(file.path(system.file(package="SWOMSE"), "OM.html"))

2.2 Data Object

Objects of class Data contain fishery data that is used by management procedures, both within the MSE simulations and to provide real management advice.

2.2.1 Built-in Data Object

The SWOMSE package contains one object of class Data, which is populated with data from the swordfish fishery:

avail("Data")
#> [1] "SWOData"

Objects of class Data can be plotted using the summary function:

summary(SWOData, wait=FALSE)
#> Plotting Time-Series
#> Plotting Catch-at-Length
#> Plot 1 of 2

#> Plot 2 of 2

Currently the SWOData object contains catch data from 1950-2017, a standardized combined index from 1950-2016, and catch-at-length data from 1978-2015.

The data can be displayed by accessing the relevant slot in the Data object. For example, the catch data and annual CVs are stored in the Cat and CV_Cat slots:

2.2.2 Data Excel File

The swordfish data is stored in an Excel file which is included in the SWOMSE package.

The location of the Excel data file can be found using the following command:

system.file(package="SWOMSE")
#> [1] "C:/~/R/win-library/3.6/SWOMSE"

The data in the Excel file can be modified and imported back into R using the XL2Data function.

For example, suppose we copied the Excel Data file from the system location found above using system.file to “C:/users/user/desktop”. We could then modify the data stored in the Excel file, or add additional data, and then re-import by typing:

SWO_newData <- XL2Data('C:/users/users/desktop/SWO_Data.xlsx')

2.3 Management Procedures

Management procedures (functions of class MP) are applied to Data objects and return management recommendations.

MPs are applied in the MSE (i.e., to objects of class Data populated with data simulated from the operating model) and to the real fishery data (e.g., SWOData).

2.3.1 SWOMSE MPs

The SWOMSE package includes 3 very simple example MPs:

avail("MP")
#> [1] "ConstC" "Itarg1" "Itarg2"

Help documentation for the MPs is found using the usual approach in R:

?Itarg1

2.3.1.1 ConstC MP

ConstC is a simple constant catch MP, which sets a fixed TAC for all future years at the current TAC. This MP has been included to provide an simple example of how MPs are constructed in the SWOMSE package.

We will step through the code for ConstC to explain how MPs work in the SWOMSE package.

All MPs must have at least the same three arguments as ConstC: x, Data, and reps:

args(ConstC)
#> function (x, Data, reps = 100) 
#> NULL

x is the position in a Data object. When applying an MP to real data, x is always 1, because there is only one set of real fishery data. In closed-loop simulation, the model generates OM@nsim simulated data sets, and x can be any value between 1 and OM@nsim.

The second argument Data is an object of class Data, such as the swordfish data object SWOData.

The third argument reps indicates the number of replicates or samples to produce each time the MP is run.

The code for ConstC is very simple:

ConstC
#> function(x, Data, reps=100) {
#>   LastTAC <- Data@MPrec[x] # last TAC
#>   TAC <- rep(LastTAC, reps)
#>   TAC <- TACfilter(TAC)
#>   Rec <- new("Rec")
#>   Rec@TAC <- TAC
#>   Rec
#> 
#> }
#> <bytecode: 0x0000000021d77ac8>
#> <environment: namespace:SWOMSE>
#> attr(,"class")
#> [1] "MP"

The first line LastTAC <- Data@MPrec[x] takes the value from the MPrec slot, which contains the most recent (i.e., current) TAC.

For example, the “Previous TAC” in SWOData is:

SWOData@MPrec
#> [1] 13200

We then generate reps samples of this value (in this case all the samples are the same value):

TAC <- rep(LastTAC, reps)

We then pass the TAC through a filter function to check for NA or other invalid values with TAC <- TACfilter(TAC). This isn’t strictly necessary but is useful for making the MP more robust in the MSE.

Finally, we create a new object of class Rec using the new("Rec") command. All MPs must return an object of class Rec which can contain a range of different management recommendations (e.g., TAC, TAE, size limit, or spatial closure).

In this case we are only returning a TAC, so we populate the TAC slot in the Rec object and return the Rec object at the end of the function.

The ConstC MP can be applied to our SWOData object to return a management recommendation, which of course in this case is not very interesting as it is always the same as the existing TAC:

ConstC(1, SWOData)
#> TAC (median) 
#>        13200

In summary, MPs are functions that have at least these three arguments: x, Data, and reps, and return objects of class Rec.

2.3.1.2 Itarg1 MP

The Itarg1 MP is a simple index targeting MP that iteratively adjusts the TAC by up to 5%, based on the ratio of the index averaged over the last 5 years to a target index level from some point in the past.

The code for Itarg can be displayed by typing the function name in the console:

Itarg1
#> function(x, Data, reps = 100, yrsmth = 5, mc = 0.05) {
#> 
#>   ind <- max(1, (length(Data@Year) - yrsmth + 1)):length(Data@Year)
#> 
#>   deltaI <- mean(Data@Ind[x, ind], na.rm=TRUE)/Data@Iref[x]
#> 
#>   if (deltaI < (1 - mc)) deltaI <- 1 - mc
#>   if (deltaI > (1 + mc)) deltaI <- 1 + mc
#>   Ind_CV <- mean(Data@CV_Ind[x,ind], na.rm=TRUE)
#>   if (is.na(Ind_CV)) Ind_CV <-  mean(Data@CV_Ind[x,], na.rm=TRUE)
#> 
#>   TAC <- Data@MPrec[x] * deltaI * trlnorm(reps, 1, Ind_CV)
#> 
#>   Rec <- new("Rec")
#>   Rec@TAC <- TACfilter(TAC)
#>   Rec
#> }
#> <bytecode: 0x000000002253c9c8>
#> <environment: namespace:SWOMSE>
#> attr(,"class")
#> [1] "MP"

Here we first calculate an index for the last yrsmth years (default value of 5 years):

ind <- max(1, (length(Data@Year) - yrsmth + 1)):length(Data@Year)

Then we calculate the average index over the most recent 5 years (ignoring an NAs in the index), and compare it to the index reference value stored in the Iref slot.

The Data@Iref slot contains the “Index Reference” value; i.e., a target level for the index.

For example, SWOData@Iref has a value of 375, which for was included for demonstration purposes and based on an average index level from the 1970-1980 period:

mean(SWOData@Ind[1,SWOData@Year %in% 1970:1980], na.rm=TRUE)
#> [1] 375.4857

The remainder of the Itarg1 code generates reps samples of a new TAC based on the mean CV in the index over the last 5 years (Data@CV_Ind), and returns a Rec object with the TAC slot populated.

2.3.1.3 Itarg2 MP

The Itarg2 MP is similiar to Itarg1 but rather than use a fixed index target (i.e, Data@Iref), it calculates a target index level based on the mean index over the last 5 years and over the last 10 years.

This MP is based on an MP developed by Geromont and Butterworth (2015) (see ?Itarg2 for reference details) and has been included to provide another slightly more complex example of an index targeting MP.

2.3.2 Creating Custom MPs

The SWOMSE package is extensible, and it is straightforward to create custom MPs and test them in the MSE.

Management procedures can be as simple (e.g., a fixed size limit) or as complex (e.g., a statisical catch-at-age assessment model) as necessary.

To be a valid MP a function must meet three criteria:

  • function must have x, Data, and reps as the first 3 arguments
  • function must return an object of class Rec
  • and function must be of class MP

For example, to create a simple MP that calculates average catch and sets this as a fixed TAC:

AverageC <- function(x, Data, reps) {
  Rec <- new("Rec")
  Rec@TAC <- rep(mean(Data@Cat[x,], na.rm = TRUE), reps)
  Rec
}
class(AverageC) <- "MP"

The new MP is now available to be tested in closed-loop simulation testing (demonstrated later in the user guide) or applied to fishery data:

avail("MP")
#> [1] "ConstC"   "Itarg1"   "Itarg2"   "AverageC"
AverageC(1,SWOData)
#> TAC (median) 
#>     10389.19

More details on creating custom MPs can be found in the relevant chapter of the DLMtool user manual.

2.3.4 Applying MPs

As demonstrated earlier, the MPs can be applied to an object of class Data to provide management recommendations.

For example, here we apply the 4 MPs that are now available to our SWOData:

mps <- avail("MP")
mps # three SWOMSE package MPs and one custom MP
#> [1] "ConstC"   "Itarg1"   "Itarg2"   "AverageC"

We use the runMP function to run the four MPs simultaneously, and increase reps to a higher value:

SWOData <- runMP(SWOData, mps, reps=1000)
#>               TAC
#> ConstC   13200.00
#> Itarg1   12274.31
#> Itarg2    6053.34
#> AverageC 10389.19

The runMP function returns an object of class Data with the TAC slot populated.

We can plot the distributions of TAC recommendations from the 4 MPs (note that, in this case, only Itarg1 includes uncertainty):

plot(SWOData)

These median TAC recommendations from these four exampe MPs are quite different.

To evalute which MP is most appropriate to achieve our fishery objectives we need to test the MPs using closed-loop simulation testing - i.e, run a MSE.

3 Management Strategy Evaluation

The runMSE function is used to run a management strategy evaluation.

To run an MSE we need to provide runMSE with an operating model and the names of the MPs we wish to test.

3.1 Conditioning OM with Data

In default mode, runMSE will generate ‘observed’ fishery data from the population dynamics that are simulated with the parameters in the OM.

To ensure that the simulated index in Data@Ind is the same as our actual index, we must provide the OM with our fishery data object:

SWOM@cpars$Data <- SWOData

Now the index in the simulated Data object used in the MSE will exactly match the index in our Data object.

The statistical properties of the index (i.e., hyper-stability parameter and variance) are calculated by comparing the standardized index with the simulated population, and these observation error parameters are used to generate comparable index values for the future projection years.

The same concept applies for any additional indices that may be present in Data@AddInd.

3.2 Performance Metrics

Before running the MSE it is important to develop performance statistics that will be used to evaluate the performance of the different management procedures.

The SWOMSE package follows the DLMtool and MSEtool packages in using standardized functions of class PM to calculate performance metrics.

We can use either the available Performance Metrics methods from the DLMtool and MSEtool packages, or create our own custom functions of class PM.

3.2.1 DLMtool Package PMs

In this demonstration we will use three of the built-in PM functions from the DLMtool and MSEtool packages and create two of our own.

The three PMs from the DLMtool package:

  • AAVY - the probability that the average annual variability in yield is less than 20%
  • P50 - the probability that spawning biomass \((\text{SB})\) is greater than \(0.5\text{SB}_{\text{MSY}}\)
  • PNOF - the probability that fishing mortality (\(F\)) is less than \(F_\text{MSY}\)

By default these performance statistics are calculated over all projection years, although it is straightforward to modify this assumption.

3.2.2 SWOMSE Package PMs

Two custom PMs are included in the SWOMSE package: the average yield in the first 10 years (short-term catch; STC) and in the last 10 years (long-term catch; LTC) of the projection period.

avail("PM")
#> [1] "STC" "LTC"

3.2.3 Custom PMs

Similiar to MPs, it is straightforward to create custom PM functions. The DLMtool user manual describes how to create custom PM functions and use them in the MSE analysis.

3.3 More details on the Operating Model

Some final details on the Operating Model before we run an example MSE.

3.3.1 Observation and Implementation Error

As mentioned earlier, in addition to the parameters for the stock and fleet dynamics, the Operating Model also includes parameters for observation and implementation processes.

For purposes of demonstration the OM objects in the SWOMSE package assume very little observation error and no implementation error; for example:

SWOM@Mbiascv # no uncertainty in natural mortality parameter (observation error)
#> [1] 0.01
SWOM@TACFrac # TACs are assumed to be caught exactly (implementation error)
#> [1] 1 1

Note that because we provided the real Data object in the SWOM object, the catch and index observation parameters are calculated internally and the relevant values in the OM (catch: SWOM@Cobs and SWOM@Cbias and index: SWOM@beta and SWOM@Iobs) are ignored.

Alternative assumptions for observation or implementation error can be included by modifying the values in the relevant slots, or by replacing the Observation and/or Implementation parameters with other built-in parameter sets, for example:

avail("Obs", "all") # all availabe Observation parameter sets 
#> [1] "Generic_Obs"        "Imprecise_Biased"   "Imprecise_Unbiased"
#> [4] "Perfect_Info"       "Precise_Biased"     "Precise_Unbiased"
# create new OM with Imprecise and Biased observation parameters
SWOM_impbiased <- Replace(SWOM, Imprecise_Biased) 
#> Replacing sub-model: Obs

avail("Imp", "all") # all availabe Implementation parameter sets 
#> [1] "Overages"    "Perfect_Imp"
# create new OM with TAC overage implementation parameters
SWOM_overage <- Replace(SWOM, Overages) 
#> Replacing sub-model: Imp

3.3.2 Projection Period & Management Interval

The number of projection years in is specified with the proyears slot in the OM object. In this case, the OMs in the SWOMSE package include a 50-year projection period:

SWOM@proyears
#> [1] 50

We can decrease the number of projection years by changing the value in SWOM@proyears to a smaller value.

However, because the OMs were created directly from SS OMs using the SWO_SS2OM function, we cannot increase the number of projection years without re-importing the SS OMs.

The OM@interval slot species the management interval. For example, the OMs in the SWOMSE package have a interval value of 4, which means that the MPs will be applied every 4 years, with the TAC held constant in the interim years.

Similiar to the proyears argument, we can easily change the management interval by setting the value in SWOM@interval to any positive integer value.

3.4 Running the MSE

We now have everything to run an example MSE:

  • operating model: SWOM, conditioned with SWOData
  • MPs: avail("MP")

Remember, the SWOM has 174 simulations (SWOM@nsim): corresponding to the base case SS OM, and the 173 SS OMs from the uncertainty grid. This means that the MSE will generate 174 simulations in every time-step, and simultaneously apply the MPs to all simulations.

Because there are a large number of simulations we will run the MSE using parallel processing (parallel=TRUE). Update messages are not available in parallel mode, but the MSE runs substantially quicker when using parallel mode.

Set up parallel processing (ignore the warning message):

setup() 
#> Warning in searchCommandline(parallel, cpus = cpus, type = type,
#> socketHosts = socketHosts, : Unknown option on commandline:
#> rmarkdown::render('C:/Users/Adrian/Documents/GitHub/SWOMSE/doc/
#> userguide.Rmd', encoding
#> R Version:  R version 3.6.1 (2019-07-05)
#> snowfall 1.84-6.1 initialized (using snow 0.4-3): parallel execution on 8 CPUs.
#> Library DLMtool loaded.
#> Library DLMtool loaded in cluster.
#> Library MSEtool loaded.
#> Library MSEtool loaded in cluster.

And run the MSE (may take a few minutes):

MPs <- avail("MP") # the MPs that will be run
SWOM@cpars$Data <- SWOData # for clarity, re-add SWOData to the OM

SWO_MSE <- runMSE(SWOM, MPs=MPs, parallel = TRUE)

The runMSE function returns the completed MSE in an object of class MSE:

class(SWO_MSE)
#> [1] "MSE"
#> attr(,"package")
#> [1] "DLMtool"

3.5 Examining MSE Results

Now that the MSE is complete we can evaluate the MPs with our performance metrics.

3.5.1 Convergence Diagnostics

First we will confirm that the MSE has converged:

Converge(SWO_MSE)
#> Checking if order of MPs is changing in last 20 iterations
#> Checking average difference in PM over last 20 iterations is > 0.5
#> Plotting MPs 1 - 4

This plot confirms that enough simulations have been included in the MSE to obtain stable results.

3.5.2 Summarizing Performance

We can summarize the performance of the MPs with our performance metrics functions:

PMlist <- c(avail("PM"), "AAVY", "P50", "PNOF") 
summary(SWO_MSE, PMlist=PMlist)
#> Calculating Performance Metrics
#>                                Performance.Metrics 
#> 1             Mean Short-Term Yield \n(Years 1-10) 
#> 2             Mean Long-Term Yield \n(Years 41-50) 
#> 3 Average Annual Variability in Yield (Years 1-50) 
#> 4               Spawning Biomass relative to SBMSY 
#> 5          Probability of not overfishing (F<FMSY) 
#>                                       
#> 1 Mean Short-Term Yield \n(Years 1-10)
#> 2 Mean Long-Term Yield \n(Years 41-50)
#> 3        Prob. AAVY < 20% (Years 1-50)
#> 4  Prob. SB > 0.5 SBMSY (Years 1 - 50)
#> 5        Prob. F < FMSY (Years 1 - 50)
#> 
#> 
#> Performance Statistics:
#>         MP   STC   LTC AAVY  P50 PNOF
#> 1 AverageC 10000 10000 0.99 0.99 0.90
#> 2   ConstC 12000 11000 0.91 0.92 0.73
#> 3   Itarg1 13000  3400 0.13 0.62 0.36
#> 4   Itarg2  7000  7800 1.00 1.00 0.98

Note that the performance statistics are calculated over all simulations in the MSE. In this case, where our OM SWOM includes all available SS OMs (base case and from uncertainty grid) the performance metrics are calculated across all SS OMs.

We can re-run the MSE with individual SS OMs (e.g., OM_19) to evaluate performance of the MPs under only those conditions.

3.5.3 Plotting MSE Results

There are several functions for presenting the MSE results graphically.

For example, trade-off plots with our performance metrics can be created with TradePlot:

TradePlot(SWO_MSE, Lims=0, PMlist=PMlist)
#> Odd number of PMs. Recycling first PM
#> Recycling limits

#>         MP   STC   LTC AAVY  P50 PNOF Satisificed
#> 1 AverageC 10000 10000 0.99 0.99 0.90        TRUE
#> 2   ConstC 12000 11000 0.91 0.92 0.73        TRUE
#> 3   Itarg1 13000  3400 0.13 0.62 0.36        TRUE
#> 4   Itarg2  7000  7800 1.00 1.00 0.98        TRUE

Projection plots of F/FMSY and B/BMSY for the individual simulations:

Pplot(SWO_MSE)

Kobe-type plots:

Kplot(SWO_MSE)

and wormplots:

wormplot(SWO_MSE)
